You can&#39;t use the ternary operator to call void methods, but you can drop the second conditional check and just use `else`. After all, if `Objects.equals(message, Const.CONFIRMATION)` is `false`, then it is clear that `!Objects.equals(message, Const.CONFIRMATION)` is true.

```java
if (Objects.equals(message, Const.CONFIRMATION)) {
	response.setMessage(message);
	response.setCodeStatut(Const.HTTP_200);
	response.setNumPolice(c.getNumPolice());
	responseRepository.save(response);
} else {
	response.setMessage(message);
	response.setCodeStatut(Const.HTTP_400);
}
```

The answer is &quot;yes&quot;; you can replace all your code with one (ugly) ternary statement:

```
return Objects.equals(message, Const.CONFIRMATION) ?
    new Response() {{
        setMessage(message);
        setCodeStatut(Const.HTTP_200);
        setNumPolice(c.getNumPolice());
        responseRepository.save(this);
    }} :
    new Response() {{
        setMessage(this);
        setCodeStatut(Const.HTTP_400);
    }};
```

However! Just because you *can* do something, don&#39;t mean you *should*. Readability, which includes adherence to convention, is paramount and this code is neither. Further, this implementation suffers from [allowing `this` to escape](https://wiki.sei.cmu.edu/confluence/plugins/servlet/mobile?contentId=88487816#content/view/88487816).

In short, *don&#39;t try this at home*.

You cannot use the ternary operator for this job without doing at least one of:

* Redesigning the API of Response, in which case there are far better things you can do here to clean this code up and make code that uses that class be shorter and simpler.
* Using nasty hacks. As in, seems to work, but can cause extremely serious, many _hours_ of wasted time serious effects later on side-effects, and doesn&#39;t stack to anything even remotely resembling common code style guidelines.

Hence, don&#39;t.

If you&#39;d like this code to be golfed down without resorting to nastiness:

```
var response = new Response();
response.setMessage(message);
response.setCodeStatut(Const.HTTP_400);
if (Const.CONFIRMATION.equals(message)) {
  response.setCodeStatut(Const.HTTP_200);
  response.setNumPolice(c.getNumPolice());
  responseRepository.save(response);
}

return response;
```

* `Objects.equals` is a somewhat dubious tool that can be used if you want to consider `null` to be equal to `null` (that&#39;s the dubious part). `Const.CONFIRMATION` surely isn&#39;t `null`, or if it is, make that `if (message == null)` instead. Hence, no need for it.
* The `else` clause wouldn&#39;t compile, but the intent is clearly just `else`, no need to repeat the negative variant of the same rule.
* Once we&#39;re down to that level, `response.setMessage(message)` is always executed, so, you can just do that up top.
* Possibly dubious, but presuming that `setCodeStatut` is a trivial setter, you can just invoke it a second time and avoid the else entirely from there.

* The reason you can&#39;t use the ternary operator, is because the ternary operator can only be used with expressions, and a block of statements isn&#39;t an expression. There are hacks, but they are just that: Create nasty side-effects, and are so non-standard, they need a hefty comment to explain why no ready alternative will do. That would be a lie, so don&#39;t apply the hackery.

You *could* do this with a helper function:

```
    static Response myFunc() {
        Response response = new Response();
        if (Objects.equals(message, Const.CONFIRMATION)) {
            return createResponse(message, Const.HTTP_200, r -&gt; {
                r.setNumPolice(c.getNumPolice());
                responseRepository.save(r);
            });
        } else {
            return createResponse(message, Const.HTTP_400, r -&gt; {});
        }

        return response;
    }

    static Response createResponse(String message, int status, Consumer&lt;Response&gt; sideEffects) {
        Response response = new Response();
        response.setMessage(message);
        response.setStatus(status);
        sideEffects.accept(response);
        return response;
    }
```
and with the helper function and a ternary operator:
```
        static Response myFunc() {
        return Objects.equals(message, Const.CONFIRMATION)
                ? createResponse(message, Const.HTTP_200, r -&gt; {
                        r.setNumPolice(c.getNumPolice());
                        responseRepository.save(r);
                    })
                : createResponse(message, Const.HTTP_400, r -&gt; {});
        }
```

The advantage of this approach is that you can&#39;t forget to set the `message` or the `status`, and the specific other operations you do to the response are kept collected in a single block.

Perhaps this introduces too much extra cognitive load when you read the code, and perhaps in this implementation it is too easy to bypass `createResponse` when you are maintaining the code, but in general creating a small function to remove duplication and to make it easier for developers to follow conventions (or patterns for the use of particular classes) is useful.

As others have said, redesigning `Response` would be a good idea, but if it was a third party class something like this approach would be useful.

